aVPhilippe Léglise-Costa will be on the front line in negotiating the EU's long-term budget | Bertrand Langlois/AFP via Getty Images France to name Philippe Léglise-Costa as new EU ambassador The veteran civil servant will be on the front lines of advancing Macron\u2019s agenda on the world stage.\u000a\u000aPARIS \u2014 France\u2019s next ambassador to the European Union will be Philippe Léglise-Costa, a high-ranking civil servant deeply versed in EU affairs, officials involved in his nomination told POLITICO.\u000a\u000aLéglise-Costa, who currently runs the European Affairs Directorate out of the prime minister\u2019s office, will take over from veteran diplomat Pierre Sellal when he heads into retirement sometime in October, the officials said.\u000a\u000aBeing France\u2019s permanent representative to the EU will thrust Léglise-Costa \u2014 who was EU adviser to President François Hollande when Emmanuel Macron was deputy chief of staff \u2014 into the heart of European affairs at a decisive moment for the Union.\u000a\u000aBrexit negotiations will be a major area of focus at least for the first two years of his mandate, whether or not they reach a conclusion.\u000a\u000aLéglise-Costa will be on the front line in negotiating the EU\u2019s long-term budget, known as the multiannual financial framework, a lengthy and complex process that involves jockeying between member states.\u000a\u000aAlso high on Léglise-Costa\u2019s agenda will be seeing through European Commission President Jean-Claude Juncker\u2019s investment agenda, while preparing for European Parliament elections in 2019 that are seen as a litmus test for Euroskepticism across the bloc.\u000a\u000aBut his overarching duty will be to advance France\u2019s agenda on the European stage, with a mandate from President Macron to press for deeper integration in areas ranging from security to defense and border control.\u000a\u000aMacron campaigned on an ambitious promise of fixing imbalances in the eurozone by establishing a standalone budget, a finance minister and possibly even a parliament for the common currency area.\u000a\u000aFor now, German Chancellor Angela Merkel has been open to Macron\u2019s ideas but reserved, as she stopped short of embracing any plans to pool funds or risks ahead of Germany\u2019s parliamentary election in September.\u000a\u000aBut a French diplomat told POLITICO that the likelihood of Merkel being reelected opens up a four-year period of stability in Europe\u2019s two biggest countries which would set the conditions for major advances. If Britain leaves the EU, then France and Germany will carry even greater weight, and the eurozone, along with its Nordic neighbors, will be in a strong position to press forward with deeper integration.\u000a\u000aCrucial trio\u000a\u000aA graduate of the elite Polytechnique University, the Toulouse native is taking over as permanent representative after a string of high-level posts including deputy permanent representative to the EU and European affairs sherpa to the president until 2017.\u000a\u000aAt the permanent representation, Léglise-Costa will be in constant contact with Macron\u2019s inner circle, notably his diplomatic adviser, Philippe Etienne, and his EU and G20 adviser, Clément Beaune.\u000a\u000aLéglise-Costa and Etienne have a decades-long working relationship, and he and Beaune were in close contact when the latter was advising Macron on EU affairs at the finance ministry.\u000a\u000aIn close coordination with Macron, the three men will be in charge of fine-tuning French day-to-day policy on the European stage, with Etienne taking a special interest in Germany and Beaune well-versed in trade and anti-dumping issues.\u000a\u000aThe new ambassador is known for his mastery of EU affairs and mechanics. He will have to prove during his first few months that he can embrace the role\u2019s more political and outward-facing aspects, at which his predecessor Sellal excelled.\u000a\u000aAt the European Affairs Directorate of the prime minister\u2019s office, Léglise-Costa is likely to be succeeded by Alexis Dutertre, who was deputy permanent representative before returning to France this year.\u000a\u000aThe nominations, three months into Macron\u2019s presidency, are expected to be announced in the coming weeks. They come amid intensive maneuvering for coveted diplomatic jobs across the French network.\u000a\u000aAmbassador to the United States Gérard Araud is expected to remain in his post, while China envoy Maurice Gourdault-Montagne took over as secretary-general of the foreign ministry.\u000a\u000aAnne-Marie Descôtes took over from Etienne as French ambassador to Berlin.
