aVA British bank note, controversially made using animal products | Justin Tallis/AFP via Getty Images Bank of England to keep animal products in banknotes despite public outcry The central bank said that after \u2018careful and serious consideration and extensive public consultation\u2019 there would be no change to the composition of polymer used in banknotes.\u000a\u000aThe Bank of England announced today it would continue to use polymer containing trace amounts of animal products in bank notes, despite a public outcry from vegetarians, vegans and religious groups.\u000a\u000aIn a statement, the central bank said that after \u201ccareful and serious consideration and extensive public consultation\u201d there would be no change to the composition of polymer used in future banknotes.\u000a\u000a\u201cThe new polymer £20 note and future print runs of £5 and £10 notes will continue to be made from polymer manufactured using trace amounts of chemicals, typically less than 0.05 percent, ultimately derived from animal products,\u201d the statement read.\u000a\u000aA petition launched in November called on the Bank of England to remove tallow \u2014 which is made from rendered animal fat \u2014 from British bank notes. Some 137,000 people signed the petition calling on the bank to use palm oil, citing the objections of vegetarians, vegans, Hindus, Sikhs, Jains and others in the U.K.\u000a\u000aIn a public consultation of more than 3,500 people led by the bank, 88 percent of respondents said they opposed the use of animal fats in the manufacturing of bank notes.\u000a\u000aThe Bank of England doesn\u2019t consider palm oil to be a viable alternative. It cited concerns that suppliers could not commit to sourcing the highest quality palm oil, as well as additional costs \u2014 which could amount to £16.5 million over the next 10 years.\u000a\u000aIn February the Bank of England announced that it would not withdraw new plastic £5 notes from circulation, despite the petition.
