aVThe Pentagon has said that it does not consider Trump's tweets official policy and is awaiting or more formal guidance before implementing any changes in regulations. Five transgender troops sue Trump over potential ban\u000a\u000aFive transgender members of the military have filed suit against President Donald Trump over his stated intent to reinstate a ban on transgender troops.\u000a\u000aIn Doe v. Trump, the anonymous service members are challenging Trump's announcement last month via a series of tweets that transgender people will not be able to serve "in any capacity."\u000a\u000aStory Continued Below\u000a\u000a\u201cLast year, the Department of Defense announced that transgender people could serve openly,\u201d one of the plaintiffs said in a statement. \u201cI was very relieved and came out as transgender to my commanding officers, who were supportive. My experience has been positive and I am prouder than ever to continue to serve. I am married and have three children, and the military has been my life. But now, I\u2019m worried about my family\u2019s future.\u201d\u000a\u000aThe troops are being represented by lawyers from GLBTQ Legal Advocates & Defenders and the National Center for Lesbian Rights.\u000a\u000aThe suit, which was filed in the U.S. District Court for the District of Columbia, "rests on claims of equal protection, due process and estoppel," the advocacy groups said in a statement, or the "inequity of the reversal of military policy after thousands of service members followed protocol and informed their chain of command that they are transgender."\u000a\u000aThe Pentagon has said that it does not consider Trump's tweets official policy and is awaiting or more formal guidance before implementing any changes in regulations.\u000a\u000a\u000a\u000aAuthors:\u000a\u000aThis story tagged under: Military\u000a\u000aTransgender
