aVStephan Weil, Lower Saxony's Social Democrat premier | Holger Hollemann/AFP via Getty Images German state premier under pressure to quit after double trouble SPD\u2019s Stephan Weil accused of allowing VW to edit a speech.\u000a\u000aThe head of the German state of Lower Saxony has been urged to quit following twin crises in a matter of days.\u000a\u000aGerman media reported at the weekend that Stephan Weil, the state\u2019s Social Democrat premier, had allowed Volkswagen to edit a speech he gave on the Dieselgate emissions scandal.\u000a\u000aThe controversy comes less than seven weeks ahead of federal elections, in which Weil\u2019s party hopes to oust Chancellor Angela Merkel, and days after Weil\u2019s coalition government was brought down by a single lawmaker\u2019s surprise defection.\u000a\u000aAndreas Scheuer, general secretary of the Christian Social Union, the Bavarian sister party of Merkel\u2019s Christian Democrats, called Weil\u2019s VW decision \u201cdownright scandalous\u201d and demanded his resignation, according to regional daily Passauer Neue Presse.\u000a\u000aWeil is accused of having sought Volkswagen\u2019s blessing for a speech in parliament he gave in the midst of the VW emissions scandal in 2015. The carmaker received an advance copy of the speech, removing \u201cproblematic sections\u201d and adding \u201cpositive formulations,\u201d Bild am Sonntag reported.\u000a\u000aWeil and the Social Democrats (SPD) vehemently rejected accusations of wrongdoing, saying his consultations with the carmaker were innocuous and had long been known.\u000a\u000a\u201cThis purportedly new trouble is old news and was already discussed in Lower Saxony over a year ago. It\u2019s election maneuvering,\u201d Weil told the paper.\u000a\u000aWeil argued that the emissions scandal required him to weigh his words carefully to avoid unduly causing massive losses at Volkswagen. On Sunday, his regional government published a draft of the 2015 speech in an attempt to show that the state premier merely sought legal and technical advice from the carmaker.\u000a\u000aThe draft appears to show that stern criticisms of VW\u2019s behavior were not removed from the text after it was sent to the carmaker. However, a sentence on the legal implications of Volkswagen\u2019s behavior was amended at the company\u2019s behest.\u000a\u000aThe VW spat comes hot on the heels of yet more trouble for Weil and the SPD. On Friday, Green MP Elke Twesten switched her allegiance to the Christian Democrats, meaning the SPD-Green governing coalition lost its one-seat majority.\u000a\u000aSpeaking at a hastily convened press conference after Twesten\u2019s announcement Friday, Weil said he supported calling a new election, but ruled out stepping down. A snap election is scheduled for October 15.\u000a\u000aOther SPD leaders raised questions about whether the conservatives had made secret promises to buy the Green lawmaker\u2019s allegiance.\u000a\u000a\u201cThis is a clumsy attempt at discrediting Stephan Weil\u2019s successful government and to distract from the machinations of the CDU,\u201d said the SPD\u2019s vice chairman, Ralf Stegner.\u000a\u000aFellow Social Democrat Thomas Oppermann, head of the party in the national parliament, added: \u201cI want to know if there was more, or if further promises were made by the CDU in Lower Saxony.\u201d\u000a\u000aAuthors:
