aVMost people appear to see Brexit as a thing which is happening, not a debating point. At least for now | Leon Neal/Getty Images Brexit Files Insight Why an anti-Brexit party is unlikely David Davis\u2019 chief adviser goes rogue on Twitter, but his suggestion that Britain needs a new party unlikely to gain traction.\u000a\u000aDavid Davis\u2019s former chief adviser, James Chapman, may have gone rogue but he is not the only British government insider who thinks Brexit will be a disaster.\u000a\u000a\u201cI\u2019ve not met a single person in the department who voted for Brexit,\u201d one official admitted to POLITICO recently. You\u2019d be hard pressed to find a Brexiteer in the U.K.\u2019s representation in Brussels either.\u000a\u000aAfter a year in government Chapman believes the only answer is to call Brexit off and establish a new centrist party \u2014 perhaps under the guiding hand of his old boss and political soulmate George Osborne? \u2014 to \u201cresist\u201d Britain\u2019s exit.\u000a\u000aInside the Department for Exiting the European Union there is a widespread problem of morale, with junior staff leaving and even senior directors unhappy with how things are being handled, according to government officials speaking on condition of anonymity.\u000a\u000aMost of the grumbling, however, is not to do with Brexit. What is exercising officials is far more prosaic \u2014 HR problems that come with setting up a new department, pay and conditions mainly, and accusations of bad management.\u000a\u000aWhen it comes to it, most people appear to see Brexit as a thing which is happening, not a debating point. At least for now. And in that sense staff are a microcosm for the British population at large.\u000a\u000a\u201cNot once did somebody bring up the single market,\u201d one leading Labour shadow minister recalled, reflecting on the election.\u000a\u000aNevertheless, Chapman, a respected former political editor of the Daily Mail and then an adviser to Osborne before joining Davis in the Brexit department, has seen right into the heart of government, so his warnings should not be discarded. Like most Western democracies right now, British politics is febrile. If Brexit is the disaster he and others warn it will be \u2014 bringing unemployment and pay cuts \u2014 the mood could quickly turn.\u000a\u000aSo could an anti-Brexit party work? Early evidence suggests it\u2019s unlikely.\u000a\u000aBetween them, the Conservatives and Labour won 82.3 percent of the vote in June\u2019s election \u2014 the highest since 1970. If there is space for a new party to emerge it is hard to see it. The one party which stood on a clean anti-Brexit position, the Liberal Democrats, finished with 7 percent of the vote.\u000a\u000aBut Labour\u2019s unexpected success in June\u2019s election shows there are no rules in politics any more. If Brexit is a disaster, somebody will get the blame and, as the response to Chapman\u2019s tweets has shown, the backlash will be bitter.\u000a\u000aThis insight is from POLITICO\u2018s Brexit Files newsletter, a daily afternoon digest of the best coverage and analysis of Britain\u2019s decision to leave the EU. Read today\u2019s edition or subscribe here.
